values:
My days feel entirely spent before I even get to them. Maybe I'm just sick of reading right now, but I'm trying to get on top of stuff before the weekend hits because I want to go out. I've only "gone out" once or twice since I've been back, so this weekend is sounding really good right about now.

While shelving the periodicals a few days ago, I flipped through a magazine called the Southern Review, and came across some artwork by Billy Solitario. I absolutely love it. I found it strange, but the art made me immediately think of The Awakening, a book that we're discussing in my American Literature now. What I also found strange was that some of his art is of New Orleans, the setting for part of the book. The paintings seem to evoke the same feelings I get from reading the novel, sort of a solitary desperation (although not nearly as fatalistic as Edna's in the book). Take a look, if you want:

///www.lemieuxgalleries.com/artist_solitario.html
